Scene Segmentation Using the MovieScenes Dataset¶

Name: Sankalp Singh¶

Email: ssingh56@syr.edu¶

Challenge Overview¶

  • In this challenge, our task is to predict the scene segmentation for each movie given features for each shot
  • One scene contains a series of consecutive shots. To define the problem, we first carry out shot detection for movies and group shots afterward to form scenes, where the scene boundary detection could be regarded as a binary classification problem on shot boundaries
  • Dataset includes 64 .pkl files corresponding to 64 movies

  • Dataset features:

                 - place
             - cast
             - action
             - audio
             - shot_end_frame
             - scene_transition_boundary_ground_truth (target feature)
             - scene_transition_boundary_prediction
             - imdb_id

  • We have followed the CRISP-DM methodology to tackle the scene segmentation problem

  • CRISP-DM consists of following steps:

                  - Business & Data Understanding
              - Data Preprocessing, Wrangling and Exploratory Data Analysis
              - Modeling
              - Evaluation
              - Deployment

  • Due to lack of computing resources, we have trained our machine learning models on 10 movies instead of all the 64 movies

1) Business and Data Understanding¶

  • Here, we have loaded all .pkl files from the MovieScenes dataset
  • We have loaded the files into a python list consisting of dictionaries with all the shot features for movies
  • The shot features of each movie include - place, cast, action, audio - encoded as two-dimensional tensors, with the first dimension indicating the number of shots within a movie, and the second dimension specifying feature vectors, in this case, 2048, 512, 512, and 512, respectively
  • Other features include - shot end frame, movie title, scene transition boundary predictions
  • Target feature is the annotated - scene transition boundary ground truth

2) Data Preparation, pre-processing, wrangling and EDA¶

  • Initially, we have extracted the 2048 feature vectors for place & 512 features vectors for cast, action and audio into a list and have converted that list into separate dataframes with 2048 columns for place and 512 columns for cast, action and audio
  • We have also extracted the tensor features for shot_end_frame, imdb_id, scene_transition_boundary_prediction and scene_transition_boundary_ground_truth into lists and converted the lists into separate dataframes
  • We have appended the first element of scene_transition_boundary_prediction and scene_transition_boundary_ground_truth with a "NaN" value because scene boundary prediction is starting from the second shot
  • Finally, we have concatenated all the data frames into a single data frame that consists of all the shot features predictors for all movies and the target features ground truth
  • As part of the EDA, we have plotted a distribution plot to showcase the distribution of ground truth values as True and False present in our MovieScenes Dataset
  • We have also plotted the box plots for the 4 semantic features place, cast, action and audi against the target feature ground truth

2.1) Feature Transformation - converting the tensor features into a consolidated dataframe¶

In [88]:
# converting the tensor features into separate dataframe and merging them into a single dataframe
df_data = pd.DataFrame()

for i in range(len(data)):
    place = []
    cast = []
    action = []
    audio = []
    shot_end_frame = []
    ground_truth = []
    boundary_prediction = []
    imdb_id = []
    
    for j in range(len(data[i]['place'])):
        place.append([element.item() for element in data[i]['place'][j].flatten()])
           
    for k in range(len(data[i]['cast'])):
        cast.append([element.item() for element in data[i]['cast'][k].flatten()])      
        
    for l in range(len(data[i]['action'])):
        action.append([element.item() for element in data[i]['action'][l].flatten()]) 
   
    for m in range(len(data[i]['audio'])):
        audio.append([element.item() for element in data[i]['audio'][m].flatten()]) 
    
    ground_truth.append("NaN")
    for n in range(len(data[i]['scene_transition_boundary_ground_truth'])):
        ground_truth.append([element.item() for element in data[i]['scene_transition_boundary_ground_truth'][n].flatten()])
    
    for o in range(len(data[i]['shot_end_frame'])):
        shot_end_frame.append([element.item() for element in data[i]['shot_end_frame'][o].flatten()])
    
    boundary_prediction.append("NaN")
    for p in range(len(data[i]['scene_transition_boundary_ground_truth'])):
        boundary_prediction.append([element.item() for element in data[i]['scene_transition_boundary_prediction'][p].flatten()])
    
    for q in range(len(data[i]['place'])):
        imdb_id.append(data[i]['imdb_id'])
        
    df_place = pd.DataFrame(place)
    df_place.columns = ['place_' + str(col) for col in df_place.columns]

    df_cast = pd.DataFrame(cast)
    df_cast.columns = ['cast_' + str(col) for col in df_cast.columns]

    df_action = pd.DataFrame(action)
    df_action.columns = ['action_' + str(col) for col in df_action.columns]

    df_audio = pd.DataFrame(audio)
    df_audio.columns = ['audio_' + str(col) for col in df_audio.columns]

    df_ground_truth = pd.DataFrame(ground_truth)
    df_ground_truth.columns = ['scene_transition_boundary_ground_truth']

    df_shot_end_frame = pd.DataFrame(shot_end_frame)
    df_shot_end_frame.columns = ['shot_end_frame']

    df_boundary_prediction = pd.DataFrame(boundary_prediction)
    df_boundary_prediction.columns = ['scene_transition_boundary_prediction']

    df_imdb_id = pd.DataFrame(imdb_id)
    df_imdb_id.columns = ['imdb_id']

    df_data_movie = pd.concat([df_place, df_cast, df_action, df_audio, df_shot_end_frame, df_imdb_id, df_boundary_prediction, df_ground_truth], axis=1)

    df_data = pd.concat([df_data, df_data_movie])   
            
df_data.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)

2.3) Feature Engineering - Handling imbalanced dataset using undersampling technique¶

  • As we can see from the below distribution, the dataset is highly imbalanced with respect to the target feature - ground feature
  • To handle this imbalanced dataset problem, we have used the undersampling technique
  • We have brought down the count of overrepresented classes to match the count of underrepresented classes using a random sample which has been extracted from the original dataset

3) Model Building¶

  • Here, we have performed some pre-processing steps required for all of our machine learning models
  • We have performed a train-validation split on our training dataset using 70-30 as the size. This will help prevent our models from overfitting and we will also be able to perform hyper-parameter tuning on validation set
  • We have created a generic AUC-ROC function which will help us generate the Area Under the Receiver Operating Characrteristic curve for all the models that can predict the probability of the target class labels

MODELING APPROACHES:¶

1) We have implemented the models without using "scene_transition_boundary_prediction" as a predictor without lags

2) We have implemented the models using "scene_transition_boundary_prediction" as a predictor without lags

3) We have implemented the models using "scene_transition_boundary_prediction" as a predictor with lags

4) We have implemented the models without "scene_transition_boundary_prediction" as a predictor with lags

Evaluation Metrics:¶

  • The F1-score is a way of combining the precision and recall of the model, and it is defined as the harmonic mean of the model’s precision and recall

  • Mean Average Precision (mAP) -- AP measures the quality of scene transition predictions in a movie. Specifically, it is the mean of precisions achieved at each threshold, weighted by the increase in recall. Then mAP is the mean of all AP scores

  • Mean Maximum IoU (mean Miou) -- Miou measures how well the predicted scenes and the ground-truth scenes overlap in a movie. Then we take the mean of all Miou scores as the final score

Preparing our data for the models:¶

  • Here, we have created 4 datasets in total using our original dataset
  • 1st dataset contains - scene_transition_boundary_prediction - feature without lags
  • 2nd dataset does not contain - scene_transition_boundary_prediction - feature without lags
  • 3rd dataset contains - scene_transition_boundary_prediction - feature with lags
  • 4th dataset contains - scene_transition_boundary_prediction - feature without lags
  • We have also dropped the features - shot_end_frame & imdb_title - as they will not be useful for predicting the target feature

ROC function - generic AUC-ROC function which will help us generate the Area Under the Receiver Operating Characteristic curve for all the models that can predict the probability of the target class labels¶

In [119]:
# Function to plot ROC_AUC_curve

def ROC_AUC_curve(model,model_name="Model"):
    # generate a no skill prediction (majority class)
    ns_probs = [0 for _ in range(len(y_test))]

    # predict probabilities
    lr_probs = model.predict_proba(X_test)
    # keep probabilities for the positive outcome only
    lr_probs = lr_probs[:, 1]
    # calculate scores
    ns_auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, ns_probs)
    lr_auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, lr_probs)
    # summarize scores
    print('No Skill: ROC AUC=%.3f' % (ns_auc))
    print('Model: ROC AUC=%.3f' % (lr_auc))
    # calculate roc curves
    ns_fpr, ns_tpr, _ = roc_curve(y_test, ns_probs)
    lr_fpr, lr_tpr, _ = roc_curve(y_test, lr_probs)
    # plot the roc curve for the model
    plt.figure(figsize=(8,4))
    plt.plot(ns_fpr, ns_tpr, linestyle='--', label='No Skill')
    plt.plot(lr_fpr, lr_tpr, marker='.', label=model_name)
    # axis labels
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    # show the legend
    plt.legend()
    # show the plot
    plt.show()

Hyper-paramater tuning using GridSearch:¶

  • max_depth: This is the maximum depth till which the tree will keep on splitting. It ensures that the tree does not overfit the data
  • max_features: The max_features is the number of features that will be used for making a single tree. For eg using "sqrt", the tree uses the square root of the number of total features in the data. Using auto is the same as making use of sqrt. The other values can be specified using the int(number of features to be used less than the total features), log, and a proportion of the features to be used
  • min_samples_leaf: The minimum number of samples that should be there in leaf node. If the number is less, then the leaf node is pruned
  • min_samples_split: The number of samples that should be present in the node for it to be split further
  • n_estimators:This is an important tuning parameter for the Random Forest model. It is the number of trees to be used for predicting the result
  • n_jobs: This is a hyper-parameter used for the Grid search. n_jobs=-1 means that the computation will be dispatched on all the CPUs of the computer

  • We have implemented the Linear Support Vector Machine model here
  • We have used a 5 folds cross validation grid search to perform the hyper parameter tuning

# initializing the linear SVC model
lsvm = LinearSVC(random_state=16)

Hyper-paramater tuning using GridSearch:¶

  • C: This is the cost parameter. It is used for regularization and represents the penalty associated with misclassification. Higher C means lower bias but risk of overfitting. It also means higher complexity of decision boundary and higher number of support vectors. Similarly, lower C means higher bias but lower variance
  • penalty: This represents the penalty as l1 and l2 regularisation parameter. The l1 and l2 both penalize the points and make the models less susceptible to outliers and improve its overall generalization.
  • loss: Specifies the loss function. ‘hinge’ is the standard SVM loss (used e.g. by the SVC class) while ‘squared_hinge’ is the square of the hinge loss.
  • n_jobs: This is a hyper-parameter used for the Grid search. n_jobs=-1 means that the computation will be dispatched on all the CPUs of the computer

3.1.5) ANN - Artificial Neural Network - 1 Hidden Layer¶

  • We have implemented the Artificial Neural Network model with 1 hidden layers here
  • The ANN1 model contains an initial sequential layer followed by the dense hidden layer using activation function as 'relu' and 20 nodes followed by dense output layer that uses 'sigmoid' as the activation function in order to predict the binary labels for output class.
  • The input shape is the total number of features present in the training data i.e. 3584
  • The hidden layer contains 20 nodes of perceptrons
  • We have used the loss function as 'binary_crossentropy', optimizer as 'adam' and metrics as 'accuracy' to implement a deep learning network with 1 hidden layers
  • We have used epochs=30 and batch_size=20 for the hyperparameter tuning of the model and have calculated the loss and accuracy for both train and testing data for each epoch
  • After this, we have printed the classification report for our model on training data, validation data in order to get a sense of how well our model is performing in terms of precision, recall, f1-score and accuracy
  • We have generated an AUC-ROC curve as ANN1 model that predicts the probability of the target class labels

# initializing the RF model
rf=RandomForestClassifier(random_state=16,n_jobs=-1)

Hyper-paramater tuning using GridSearch:¶

  • max_depth: This is the maximum depth till which the tree will keep on splitting. It ensures that the tree does not overfit the data
  • max_features: The max_features is the number of features that will be used for making a single tree. For eg using "sqrt", the tree uses the square root of the number of total features in the data. Using auto is the same as making use of sqrt. The other values can be specified using the int(number of features to be used less than the total features), log, and a proportion of the features to be used
  • min_samples_leaf: The minimum number of samples that should be there in leaf node. If the number is less, then the leaf node is pruned
  • min_samples_split: The number of samples that should be present in the node for it to be split further
  • n_estimators:This is an important tuning parameter for the Random Forest model. It is the number of trees to be used for predicting the result
  • n_jobs: This is a hyper-parameter used for the Grid search. n_jobs=-1 means that the computation will be dispatched on all the CPUs of the computer
In [218]:
# Performing grid search to find the best hyper-parameters

             'min_samples_split': [10,20,30],
             'n_estimators': [5,15,30]}

Hyper-paramater tuning using GridSearch:¶

  • C: This is the cost parameter. It is the inverse of the lambda. Smaller value specify more regularization
  • Penalty: The types of penalty that can be used are l1 and l2. The l1 penalty has the characteristics of eliminating features by making its co-efficient 0. The l2 penalty does not eliminate features but it penalizes the effect of less useful features and makes their co-efficient close to 0

3.2.3) Linear Support Vector Machine¶

  • We have implemented the Linear Support Vector Machine model here
  • We have used a 5 folds cross validation grid search to perform the hyper parameter tuning
  • After this, we have printed the classification report for our model on training and testing data in order to get a sense of how well our model is performing in terms of precision, recall, f1-score and accuracy
  • We have not generated an AUC-ROC curve as SVM model does not predict the probability of the target class labels
In [239]:
# initializing the linear SVC model
lsvm = LinearSVC(random_state=16)

Hyper-paramater tuning using GridSearch:¶

  • C: This is the cost parameter. It is used for regularization and represents the penalty associated with misclassification. Higher C means lower bias but risk of overfitting. It also means higher complexity of decision boundary and higher number of support vectors. Similarly, lower C means higher bias but lower variance
  • penalty: This represents the penalty as l1 and l2 regularisation parameter. The l1 and l2 both penalize the points and make the models less susceptible to outliers and improve its overall generalization.
  • loss: Specifies the loss function. ‘hinge’ is the standard SVM loss (used e.g. by the SVC class) while ‘squared_hinge’ is the square of the hinge loss.
  • n_jobs: This is a hyper-parameter used for the Grid search. n_jobs=-1 means that the computation will be dispatched on all the CPUs of the computer
In [240]:
# Performing grid search to find the best hyper-parameters

              'loss': ['hinge', 'square_hinge']
              }

3.2.4) ANN - Artificial Neural Network - 1 Hidden Layer¶

  • We have implemented the Artificial Neural Network model with 1 hidden layers here
  • The ANN1 model contains an initial sequential layer followed by the dense hidden layer using activation function as 'relu' and 20 nodes followed by dense output layer that uses 'sigmoid' as the activation function in order to predict the binary labels for output class.
  • The input shape is the total number of features present in the training data i.e. 3585
  • The hidden layer contains 20 nodes of perceptrons
  • We have used the loss function as 'binary_crossentropy', optimizer as 'adam' and metrics as 'accuracy' to implement a deep learning network with 1 hidden layers
  • We have used epochs=30 and batch_size=20 for the hyperparameter tuning of the model and have calculated the loss and accuracy for both train and testing data for each epoch
  • After this, we have printed the classification report for our model on training data, validation data in order to get a sense of how well our model is performing in terms of precision, recall, f1-score and accuracy
  • We have generated an AUC-ROC curve as ANN1 model that predicts the probability of the target class labels
In [246]:

3.3.1) Random Forest¶

  • We have implemented the Random Forest Clasifier model here
  • We have used a 3 folds cross validation grid search to perform the hyper parameter tuning
  • After this, we have printed the classification report for our model on training data and testing data in order to get a sense of how well our model is performing in terms of precision, recall, f1-score and accuracy
  • We have also generated an AUC-ROC curve for RF model
In [391]:
# initializing the RF model
rf=RandomForestClassifier(random_state=16,n_jobs=-1)

Hyper-paramater tuning using GridSearch:¶

  • max_depth: This is the maximum depth till which the tree will keep on splitting. It ensures that the tree does not overfit the data
  • max_features: The max_features is the number of features that will be used for making a single tree. For eg using "sqrt", the tree uses the square root of the number of total features in the data. Using auto is the same as making use of sqrt. The other values can be specified using the int(number of features to be used less than the total features), log, and a proportion of the features to be used
  • min_samples_leaf: The minimum number of samples that should be there in leaf node. If the number is less, then the leaf node is pruned
  • min_samples_split: The number of samples that should be present in the node for it to be split further
  • n_estimators:This is an important tuning parameter for the Random Forest model. It is the number of trees to be used for predicting the result
  • n_jobs: This is a hyper-parameter used for the Grid search. n_jobs=-1 means that the computation will be dispatched on all the CPUs of the computer
In [274]:

             'min_samples_split': [10,20,30],

Hyper-paramater tuning using GridSearch:¶

  • C: This is the cost parameter. It is the inverse of the lambda. Smaller value specify more regularization
  • Penalty: The types of penalty that can be used are l1 and l2. The l1 penalty has the characteristics of eliminating features by making its co-efficient 0. The l2 penalty does not eliminate features but it penalizes the effect of less useful features and makes their co-efficient close to 0

3.3.3) Linear Support Vector Machine¶

  • We have implemented the Linear Support Vector Machine model here
  • We have used a 5 folds cross validation grid search to perform the hyper parameter tuning
  • After this, we have printed the classification report for our model on training and testing data in order to get a sense of how well our model is performing in terms of precision, recall, f1-score and accuracy
  • We have not generated an AUC-ROC curve as SVM model does not predict the probability of the target class labels
In [295]:
# initializing the linear SVC model
lsvm = LinearSVC(random_state=16)

Hyper-paramater tuning using GridSearch:¶

  • C: This is the cost parameter. It is used for regularization and represents the penalty associated with misclassification. Higher C means lower bias but risk of overfitting. It also means higher complexity of decision boundary and higher number of support vectors. Similarly, lower C means higher bias but lower variance
  • penalty: This represents the penalty as l1 and l2 regularisation parameter. The l1 and l2 both penalize the points and make the models less susceptible to outliers and improve its overall generalization.
  • loss: Specifies the loss function. ‘hinge’ is the standard SVM loss (used e.g. by the SVC class) while ‘squared_hinge’ is the square of the hinge loss.
  • n_jobs: This is a hyper-parameter used for the Grid search. n_jobs=-1 means that the computation will be dispatched on all the CPUs of the computer
In [296]:
# Performing grid search to find the best hyper-parameters

              'loss': ['hinge', 'square_hinge']
              }

3.3.4) ANN - Artificial Neural Network - 1 Hidden Layer¶

  • We have implemented the Artificial Neural Network model with 1 hidden layers here
  • The ANN1 model contains an initial sequential layer followed by the dense hidden layer using activation function as 'relu' and 20 nodes followed by dense output layer that uses 'sigmoid' as the activation function in order to predict the binary labels for output class.
  • The input shape is the total number of features present in the training data i.e. 7170
  • The hidden layer contains 20 nodes of perceptrons
  • We have used the loss function as 'binary_crossentropy', optimizer as 'adam' and metrics as 'accuracy' to implement a deep learning network with 1 hidden layers
  • We have used epochs=30 and batch_size=20 for the hyperparameter tuning of the model and have calculated the loss and accuracy for both train and testing data for each epoch
  • After this, we have printed the classification report for our model on training data, validation data in order to get a sense of how well our model is performing in terms of precision, recall, f1-score and accuracy
  • We have generated an AUC-ROC curve as ANN1 model that predicts the probability of the target class labels
In [305]:

3.4.1) Random Forest¶

  • We have implemented the Random Forest Clasifier model here
  • We have used a 3 folds cross validation grid search to perform the hyper parameter tuning
  • After this, we have printed the classification report for our model on training data and testing data in order to get a sense of how well our model is performing in terms of precision, recall, f1-score and accuracy
  • We have also generated an AUC-ROC curve for RF model
In [315]:
# initializing the RF model
rf=RandomForestClassifier(random_state=16,n_jobs=-1)

Hyper-paramater tuning using GridSearch:¶

  • max_depth: This is the maximum depth till which the tree will keep on splitting. It ensures that the tree does not overfit the data
  • max_features: The max_features is the number of features that will be used for making a single tree. For eg using "sqrt", the tree uses the square root of the number of total features in the data. Using auto is the same as making use of sqrt. The other values can be specified using the int(number of features to be used less than the total features), log, and a proportion of the features to be used
  • min_samples_leaf: The minimum number of samples that should be there in leaf node. If the number is less, then the leaf node is pruned
  • min_samples_split: The number of samples that should be present in the node for it to be split further
  • n_estimators:This is an important tuning parameter for the Random Forest model. It is the number of trees to be used for predicting the result
  • n_jobs: This is a hyper-parameter used for the Grid search. n_jobs=-1 means that the computation will be dispatched on all the CPUs of the computer
In [316]:

             'min_samples_split': [10,20,30],
             'n_estimators': [5,15,30]}

Hyper-paramater tuning using GridSearch:¶

3.4.3) Linear Support Vector Machine¶

  • We have implemented the Linear Support Vector Machine model here
  • We have used a 5 folds cross validation grid search to perform the hyper parameter tuning
  • After this, we have printed the classification report for our model on training and testing data in order to get a sense of how well our model is performing in terms of precision, recall, f1-score and accuracy
  • We have not generated an AUC-ROC curve as SVM model does not predict the probability of the target class labels
In [338]:
# initializing the linear SVC model
lsvm = LinearSVC(random_state=16)

Hyper-paramater tuning using GridSearch:¶

  • C: This is the cost parameter. It is used for regularization and represents the penalty associated with misclassification. Higher C means lower bias but risk of overfitting. It also means higher complexity of decision boundary and higher number of support vectors. Similarly, lower C means higher bias but lower variance
  • penalty: This represents the penalty as l1 and l2 regularisation parameter. The l1 and l2 both penalize the points and make the models less susceptible to outliers and improve its overall generalization.
  • loss: Specifies the loss function. ‘hinge’ is the standard SVM loss (used e.g. by the SVC class) while ‘squared_hinge’ is the square of the hinge loss.
  • n_jobs: This is a hyper-parameter used for the Grid search. n_jobs=-1 means that the computation will be dispatched on all the CPUs of the computer
In [339]:
# Performing grid search to find the best hyper-parameters

              }

3.4.4) ANN - Artificial Neural Network - 1 Hidden Layer¶

  • We have implemented the Artificial Neural Network model with 1 hidden layers here
  • The ANN1 model contains an initial sequential layer followed by the dense hidden layer using activation function as 'relu' and 20 nodes followed by dense output layer that uses 'sigmoid' as the activation function in order to predict the binary labels for output class.
  • The input shape is the total number of features present in the training data i.e. 7168
  • The hidden layer contains 20 nodes of perceptrons
  • We have used the loss function as 'binary_crossentropy', optimizer as 'adam' and metrics as 'accuracy' to implement a deep learning network with 1 hidden layers
  • We have used epochs=30 and batch_size=20 for the hyperparameter tuning of the model and have calculated the loss and accuracy for both train and testing data for each epoch
  • After this, we have printed the classification report for our model on training data, validation data in order to get a sense of how well our model is performing in terms of precision, recall, f1-score and accuracy
  • We have generated an AUC-ROC curve as ANN1 model that predicts the probability of the target class labels
In [345]:

5) Conclusion¶

  • We have implemented several machine learning models using 4 different approaches to predict the probability of a shot boundary being a scene boundary and hence predicting probability of scene transition
  • Logistic Regression model seems to outperform all the other models in 3 out 4 approaches that we have implemented
  • LR has performed with 90% Precision, 89% Recall, 89% F1 score, 89% Accuracy, 95.5% AUC and following hyperparameters: 'C': 0.1, 'penalty': 'l1
  • Introducing lags in the semantic features seems to be helpful in predicting the ground truths for boundary transition
  • Using the feature – scene_transition_boundary_prediction – in the models as one of the predictors also seems to be useful in predicting the ground truth labels
  • With more computing resources, we can train models for all the 64 movies similar to how we have trained them for 10 movies in this notebook
